<div id="review_346574185" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/346574185" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1040930-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1250119763p2/1040930.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/346574185?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/1040930-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1040930-laura?shelf=english-lit">english-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1040930-laura?shelf=assigned-reading">assigned-reading</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer346574185" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4246811955004485994">The problem with Shaw is that I always feel crabbier when I read him. Even <i>Pygmalion</i>, which strikes me as a superior play, makes me slightly irritable, and <i>Major Barbara</i> doesn’t have any musical tunes to hum while you’re trudging through Shaw’s dreary I Am So Keenly Critical and Nuanced dialogue. The other problem is that, in my opinion, he’s neither keen nor nuanced. He’s bigoted and cranky, and his weak humor begs an unfavorable comparison to Oscar Wilde, who probably didn’t like this play eit</span>
  <span id="freeText4246811955004485994" style="display:none">The problem with Shaw is that I always feel crabbier when I read him. Even <i>Pygmalion</i>, which strikes me as a superior play, makes me slightly irritable, and <i>Major Barbara</i> doesn’t have any musical tunes to hum while you’re trudging through Shaw’s dreary I Am So Keenly Critical and Nuanced dialogue. The other problem is that, in my opinion, he’s neither keen nor nuanced. He’s bigoted and cranky, and his weak humor begs an unfavorable comparison to Oscar Wilde, who probably didn’t like this play either. I know – Shaw brings up interesting questions about individual and corporate responsibility toward those who purchase goods, and he explores the question (impossibility) of a utopia. These are good issues, and not easily resolved in or out of the play. But Shaw’s antagonism toward religion and his disgust for human beings in general are so off-putting that I want to toss the book at his feet. Too bad someone didn’t tell him that misanthropy gets tiresome. <br /><br />In retrospect, possibly what pushed me over the edge wasn’t actually Shaw’s play, but having to listen to self-righteous classmates discuss it. “It’s awful that the Salvation Army hands out bread and soup instead of providing job training!” “Yes, in fact it’s EVIL when you think about it!” No, it’s not. Isn’t it bad enough to have to read about ridiculous characters? Must I also have to listen to ridiculous comments from actual people?? <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4246811955004485994" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


