  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2724237631" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2724237631" />
    <a title="Nick Jones" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9588678-nick-jones"><img alt="Nick Jones" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2724237631?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nick Jones" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nick Jones" href="/user/show/9588678-nick-jones">Nick Jones</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/9981805-major-barbara">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2724237631" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7732442445628893229">A drama of ideas. And there is no reason a play cannot be built on ideas rather than realistic or rounded characters. But Major Barbara generally works within the conventions of naturalism: the characters might be wittier than us, but overall they operate the way we do, at least it is implied they have the same sort of thoughts and emotions and motivations as we do. The constant danger is that Shaw’s ideas seem imposed on the characters. But, for me, that is not the central problem with Major Ba</span>
  <span id="freeText7732442445628893229" style="display:none">A drama of ideas. And there is no reason a play cannot be built on ideas rather than realistic or rounded characters. But Major Barbara generally works within the conventions of naturalism: the characters might be wittier than us, but overall they operate the way we do, at least it is implied they have the same sort of thoughts and emotions and motivations as we do. The constant danger is that Shaw’s ideas seem imposed on the characters. But, for me, that is not the central problem with Major Barbara: Major Barbara is a drama of ideas where the ideas are a little silly. As the ideas are political and Shaw was a self proclaimed socialist, we might therefore presume Major Barbara is a socialist play. But it is a strange form of socialism. Shaw can’t be accused of sentimentalising the working class: the three working class men we see at the Salvation Army Mission are a sorry bunch – a bully and braggart, a chancer who dissembles servility, and an unemployed worker whose spirit has been broken. This is not a working class that is going to politically organize itself – they need help and the play pits two forms of help against each other. On one side there is the Church...or, at least, the Salvation Army with Barbara Undershaft as their representative; on the other there is the enlightened employer, her father Andrew Undershaft – although, while he is an enlightened employer, his business is making armaments and as a good capitalist he will sell them to anyone who wishes to buy them: if he has the chance he will arm both sides in any conflict. In terms of ideas Shaw is much more sympathetic to Undershaft than the Salvation Army, but things are made more interesting than that: Barbara is a sympathetic character, while her father is a wily and manipulative scoundrel...but fun in his scoundrelness. But they are very similar in that they are practical people who sort things out – and have a ‘natural’ authority over others, i.e., they are Shavian heroes. Undershaft is a foundling: this seems to be Shaw paying lip service to a vague ideal of egalitarianism, but, in reality, both Barbara and Undershaft’s ‘natural’ authority comes from privilege: they expect people to listen to them because of their class position and sense of privilege. (The same is also true of Barbara’s mother who is charmingly bossy.) To help us navigate the play Shaw has kindly given us an identification figure, Adolphus Cusins. He is clever and witty and clear sighted, but, compared to Barbara and Undershaft, a generally passive figure. He (probably like us) is overwhelmed by Barbara’s charm and has joined the Salvation Army not through any Christian idealism, but to be near Barbara. But, in that he is a clear sighted pragmatist rather than an idealist, he is closer to Undershaft than Barbara. The case of the Salvation Army (Christianity) is undercut when Undershaft cynically ‘buys’ it by making a major financial contribution – the Salvation Army is practically ineffectual when dealing with poverty and then proves to be morally duplicitous...Barbara leaves disillusioned. The final act takes place at Undershaft’s factory and we see a model works where the employers are well paid, well housed and well looked after. The play values an enlightened capitalism over a charitable Christianity. Cusins and Barbara are won over. Despite the wit of the dialogue and the cleverness of construction (there are, for instance, some minor characters who reflect further alternatives of attitude), it is all a bit obvious: the play, like Undershaft’s factory, is a bit too regimented and tidy. But then there is the play’s silliness. Although an enlightened capitalist as an employer, Undershaft is also a down the line free trader, selling his arms with ruthless efficiency, indifferent to the consequences. When he tempts Cusins to join him he asks, “Dare you make war on war?” Other than sounding like a slogan out of Orwell’s 1984, it is difficult to know what this means. Undershaft, in contrast to the pieties of Christianity, seems to be set up as offering a totally honest and clear sighted response to the world, but in reality there is little more than a capitalist’s self legitimatization...and it ends up a little mystical. Of course, a production of the play might be able to question Undershaft’s hypocrisies (and the parallels with Christian hypocrisies) – while Barbara is at first idealistically blind to the failings of the Salvation Army, now her idealism makes her blind to the realities of her father and his methods...but this time Cusins is also drawn in. I’m not sure if such a staging would be possible: it doesn’t match the tone of the play. Rather than satirizing or exposing the hypocrisies of the powerful capitalist and his attempts to legitimize his methods, Shaw seems to celebrate him as an example of clear thinking efficiency. Shaw's contradictions should be interesting, contradictions often enrich fiction, but in a drama of ideas they just feel a little silly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7732442445628893229" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


